bio: Documenting my travels on the back roads of the US, Canada, and Mexico.

social_posts.post_text: I installed my new tires. I had to change out the spare so decided to make a video in case anyone's interested. The system works with two winches and the idea is not to have to touch the tire.  Guess I'll have to make some minor modifications.

The evolution of a table, and many other interior parts.  I went back and dug up this series of pictures to show you guys how much my table ideas have changed over the last 5 years.  It turns out the table has been one of the most difficult interior design elements for me to figure out.  These pictures also show why it may be a good idea to live in it for a bit before you come up with final plans.  First picture is the mock-up of the table. I thought I really came up with a good plan. Took plenty of time to test seating heights and table positions.  Picture 2, there is a set of drawer glides between the table top and pedestal.  I still have that pedestal if someone needs one, no not giving it away, it's worth a couple hundred bucks.  This setup proved to be too flimsy and wobbly and I didn't like the wood top. Picture 3 shows the result of a major rehab on the whole couch section. I cut a big chunk off the table and used black starboard instead of wood.  I also used a lagun mount.  Picture 4 shows the black starboard top gone because it was too heavy. Picture 5 is where we are today.  The aluminum was too cold to the touch and still too big. Felt like the table was always in the way. The table is now half its size and tight for two to eat from. We are waiting to see how this works and considering another small table lagun mount on the other side of the couch.
How the rack flexes, none, vs the frame. Watch the gap between bumper and hood.

For those who want one like mine. This is where you start. Commercialtrucktrader.com stock # 2609. I know nothing about it and have no affiliation. Just passing it along in case someone is looking.  Beware of rust from Pennsylvania.
Ah, the beauty of nature. No, not there now. This picture is from the last trip.

How does 4,240 watts of solar sound? Anyone who has lived in their camper for any amount of time knows that you can't have too much power. My friend Dan decided he didn't want to mess with low power issues. He will have somewhere around 17,000 watts of battery storage to complete the system. Dan is building a full-time bus conversion that will have all the conveniences of home including two many splits, a full sized fridge, and other "house" type conveniences.

Mini split install version 3.0. This is going to be a long winded one. Remember a while back I said that experimentation is not for the faint of heart. Well I proved that last week once again with this latest install. First, a quick recap of earlier mini split installs and why they were changed. The original install had the compressor mounted independent of the evaporator in the rear lower left compartment. I cut out the compartment bottom so the evaporator would have airflow. A few major problems with this location. Airflow was the main issue. Although it worked I had to keep the compartment door open. I considered cutting holes in the box and the door and installing auxiliary fans but luckily never got around to it. Another issue was the unit being behind the rear tire. It got very dirty and dusty. It still worked but I was convinced that it was just a matter of time before it failed back there. As it turns out mounting a compressor right below one's head is not an ideal situation for sleeping.  Who would have known?? The last issue and the one that made me eventually move the unit was that I wanted that compartment back for storage. Version 2.0 I removed the evaporator welded the bottom of the box back in and moved the evaporator onto the newly installed roof rack over the cab. Unfortunately when I made this change I crossed two wires. Now the unit would come on and then shut down within 30 seconds. I then went a full year half-heartedly trying to figure out why it didn't work. During this process I learned way too much about mini splits, and sensors and DC motors and compressor relays etc. In the end it seems it was the motherboard that I shorted. Since a motherboard cost almost as much as a new unit I ended up buying a new outside unit so I would have the option to either change out the motherboard and keep the old design or reinvent the wheel. Based on some of the issues listed above I decided it made the most sense to do the whole compressor rotate again and mount the unit on the front rack. It was a two-day job that took 10 days. The good news, I now have a working mini split that does not keep me awake is very efficient and I have my compartment.
Just because I haven't posted in awhile.

I did a thing. Because I didn't get enough attention in the big truck I decided to get a tiny one. What can I say, I don't like "normal" vehicles. This is a Subaru Sambar. Big truck is 6.6 litres, little guy is .6  It's 4wd, has A/C, heat, 6 speed including extra low 1st. Needs a little TLC but everything's there including extra parts (engine, transmission, etc.) Looking forward to using it on the place and for town runs.

Mud is the enemy. It's always risky driving this 18,000 pound beast into any kind of mud. Don't even want to think about what it would take to get me unstuck. Wasn't worried here though because it was obviously just a sandy puddle.
I'm sharing a listing for a friend. This is a very capable rig that has it all. Message me for serious inquiries.
We had an impromptu ambulance meetup by accident. Which is way better than meeting an ambulance after an accident. Great to meet Alex and see Becky and Meade again.

Going to Baja with my buddy who's never been. He's driving an old USPS truck now known as "the bread box". First off-road section I said you lead so you know when you're getting in trouble. He says sure...... uh-oh, I got in trouble. The miracle of airing down allowed the 2wd bread box to get right out.
Not all of Baja is dry. In fact it's very green now due to the recent hurricane.

location.city_name: Los Barriles, Baja California Sur, Mexico

social_posts.post_text: Living the beach life right now. The truck sure gets that lived in look in a short amount of time.

Baja is changing fast. I think there is 100% growth in La Ventana in 4 years. Luckily there are still some less crowded areas available. This isn't one of them, it just looks like it because we are the last camper on the beach.

I like doing Instagram versus reality pictures. Looks like I have the beach all to myself but in reality when you look the other way there are a couple dozen of us in a relatively small area. We are moving today to find a less crowded place.

For those of you discussing two wheel drive versus four wheel drive. We came down to Baja this year with our good buddy Dan who drives what we call the bread box. It was surprising to see how limited we were and how easily the bread box got stuck. Baja is a place where 4x4 can be put to good use. I didn't really realize that the majority of the places I go require four-wheel drive.

social_posts.post_text:
I've decided to try making my own YouTube channel. I've had many ask about it and many more ask camper advice that I keep repeating. Perhaps with my own videos and channel I can reap the benefit of all of the time and labor that I have done and will be doing.  There are many updates to the camper that most don't know about.  Please check out the new video and maybe even subscribe if you want to see more in the future. I would really appreciate some support from my Instagram community. YouTube link in the description.
Tom.
